We define a relation for comparable elements in a preorder and introduce basic API for it.

This will be used in the new [CGT repo](https://github.com/vihdzp/combinatorial-games) to define the fuzzy relation `x ‚Äñ y = ¬¨ CompRel (¬∑ ‚â§ ¬∑) x y`.

üöÄ Pull request has been placed on the maintainer queue by YaelDillies.
What's the reason to introduce the negation here? That is, is the best way to talk about two elements being comparable now to say that they are not incomparable?

I think the negation is useful since we can now completely partition the possibilities for two elements in a preorder: either `a < b`, `b < a`, `AntisymmRel (. ‚â§ .) a b` or `IncompRel (. ‚â§ .) a b`.

I'm going to second Bhavik's question, despite your answer: what's the point of this? Sure we can partiction the possibilities, but how useful is `IncompRel` in practice? What are you going to do with it?

`IncompRel` is the fuzzy relation on games, and is very relevant within their study. My goal here is to generalize this notion away from `PGame` so it can be used on all the relevant quotients of games, and for other preorders if we ever want to.

> I think the negation is useful since we can now completely partition the possibilities for two elements in a preorder: either `a < b`, `b < a`, `AntisymmRel (. ‚â§ .) a b` or `IncompRel (. ‚â§ .) a b`.

I'm not quite sure this answers the question: I could just as well write the last option as `¬¨ CompRel (. ‚â§ .) a b`. More broadly, comparability and incomparability both show up, I'd rather define comparability and write incomparability as "not comparable" vs defining incomparability and writing comparability as "not incomparable". 

But to say a bit more about the use of (either one of) these relations, these notions show up reasonably often when working with preorders and partial orders, in fact [IsChain](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Order/Chain.html#IsChain) takes in something exactly like this (and gets used in every Zorn argument in Lean). To me, `CompRel` in a partial order plays the same role as [Commute](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Group/Commute/Defs.html#Commute) does in a ring (if every pair is CompRel we have a linear order, if every pair is Commute we have a commring). 

And to tie both of these together, if we have `CompRel` then we can write `IsChain` in terms of that.
Does it ever make sense to have both? After all, just like chains use comparability, antichains use incomparability.

I don't think it does, except potentially if IncompRel is an abbrev, since they're just negations of each other. I don't believe mathlib has many pairs of definitions which are no more than negations.
Alright, I'll rework this PR when I find the time.

I've reworked this PR to define `CompRel` as the comparability relation instead - everything else is basically ported verbatim from the original PR.

I must admit this new relation is less useful to me than the former one. If I'm going to be writing things in terms of `¬¨ CompRel` then I can't use dot notation, which is annoying. Writing e.g. `IncompRel.not_le` is much nicer than writing `not_le_of_not_compRel`.

Thanks!

maintainer delegate

Small question: should this be `incompRel_refl` or `IncompRel.refl`? Likewise, should the version with implicit arguments (which I haven't added yet) be `incompRel_rfl` or `IncompRel.rfl`?

I suspect the convention we're using on `AntisymmRel` currently is wrong on both counts, but I want to make sure.
`IncompRel.refl`/`IncompRel.rfl` so that we can use it with anonymous dot notation
These lemmas will be annoying to use. Can we have applied versions?

I'd suggest swapping the definition with the one coming from the RHS of the lemma. This way:
* You don't need `incompRel_iff` as it's just the equational lemma now
* `simp [‚Üê antisymmRel_compl]` won't loop anymore
Can this move out of the `Relation` section? It's supposed to be about an arbitrary relation, not about `LE`
I'll put them at the very end, like I did with `AntisymmRel`.

But then why not do it correctly? You already have a `Preorder` section
```suggestion

end Relation

section LE

variable [LE Œ±]

theorem IncompRel.not_le (h : IncompRel (¬∑ ‚â§ ¬∑) a b) : ¬¨ a ‚â§ b := h.1
theorem IncompRel.not_ge (h : IncompRel (¬∑ ‚â§ ¬∑) a b) : ¬¨ b ‚â§ a := h.2
theorem LE.le.not_incompRel (h : a ‚â§ b) : ¬¨ IncompRel (¬∑ ‚â§ ¬∑) a b := fun h' ‚Ü¶ h'.not_le h

end LE

section Preorder
```
Alright, I've updated the `Antisymmetrization` file to match.

```

```

```suggestion
theorem CompRel.rfl [IsRefl Œ± r] : CompRel r a a := .refl ..
```
